{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01GWX3aRuNF5bELJKYoyUz9A","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a clear picture of the non-default configuration:\n\n**Non-default settings (compared to a fresh RabbitMQ install):**\n\nFresh RabbitMQ defaults:\n- Vhosts: `/` only\n- Users: `guest` (with password `guest`, administrator tag) — but in Kubernetes setups, often a custom admin user is set up\n- Permissions: `guest` has `.*` permissions on `/`\n- Policies: none\n- Queues: none\n\nCurrent state:\n1. **Extra vhosts**: `/app`, `/ops` (non-default)\n2. **Extra users**: `app-user` (management tag), `ops-user` (management tag) — `admin` is also non-default (default would be `guest`)\n3. **Permissions**: Both `/app` and `/ops` have full permissions (`.*,.*,.*`) granted to their respective users and the admin user\n4. **High availability policy**: The `/app` vhost has an `ha-all` policy that replicates queues across all nodes\n5. **Application queues**: `app-queue` and `ops-queue` are durable classic queues on their respective vhosts, while the standard RabbitMQ exchanges remain unchanged\n\nNow I'm thinking through a rollback script that would systematically remove these non-default configurations — deleting the HA policy, removing both queues, revoking user permissions, and deleting the custom users and vhosts. I need to consider whether the `admin` user should be preserved since it might be managed by the Kubernetes operator, though the task asks to revert everything to RabbitMQ defaults where the standard user is `guest`. I need to be more precise about what constitutes RabbitMQ defaults. The standard installation includes only the `/` vhost and `guest` user, so I should remove the custom vhosts and users, delete the `ha-all` policy, and clear out the application queues to restore that baseline state. preserve cluster manageability. The script will systematically remove the application-specific configurations—policies, queues, user permissions, users, and vhosts—while keeping the operator-managed `admin` user intact since deleting it would break cluster access.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":719,"cache_read_input_tokens":32078,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":719},"output_tokens":12,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"718fd708-d3d0-414d-b238-78afdaa4f241","uuid":"a02a8812-1542-420b-b264-8c450791daa1","request_id":"req_011CcLto5LCnmaAJWmnPZ7Hu"}
